   [12]Melissa Nobles
   Chancellor

                        Risks and costs of unionization

   March 24, 2022

Highlights

     o A decision to form a union carries potential risks, losses, and costs.
     o Strikes are a reality with graduate student unions: The UE calls for
       the use of strikes as "the primary weapon against the employer";
       Columbia's student union secured a contract after five years and 132
       days on strike.
     o MIT's nimble, student-driven stipend process is able to deliver much
       stronger results in a high-inflation environment than union-negotiated
       contracts at Harvard or Columbia.
     o Union members may pay dues of up to $550 per year, without any
       guarantee of better compensation or benefits.
     o A union would change campus dynamics, adding the UE as a new entity
       with its own political and financial interests; the UE and local union
       leadership may continue to access and use students' personal
       information even after a victory.
     o Some faculty are questioning how student-advisor relationships would
       be impacted, concerned that unionization "reduces flexibility in favor
       of a highly structured relationship."


   --------------------------------------------------------------------------

   To MIT graduate students:

   On April 4 and 5, many of you will participate in a confidential
   [13]election to decide whether the [14]United Electrical, Radio & Machine
   Workers of America (UE) will represent you for collective bargaining.

   We've previously described [15]our position, the [16]limits of
   unionization and labor bargaining in graduate education, and the [17]gains
   won for all MIT graduate students through our current collaborative
   processes. Today we share some of the risks, losses, and costs that
   graduate students might face if a union is elected:

     o The risk of strikes and disruptions: Strikes and delays can occur
       during contract negotiations. In fact, the [18]UE's policy book
       2021-2023 calls for "the continued use of the strike as the primary
       weapon against the employer."

       It took Columbia's student union more than five years to reach a first
       contract following its election, and students were on strike for a
       total of 132 days during this period. [19]In all cases, between 475
       and 1,504 days elapsed before a first contract was reached between
       student unions and private universities, and strikes are very possible
       during negotiations, putting academic progress at risk and important
       financial and policy improvements on hold.

     o The likely loss of a nimble, responsive, and student-driven stipend
       process: Harvard and Columbia's students are now locked into
       multi-year, union-negotiated contracts with 3 percent increases in the
       out years. By contrast, [20]our student-led process considers
       cost-of-living increases on an annual basis, and is responsive to
       high-inflation pressures such as those that exist today. As a result
       of this process, MIT's stipends are already higher than those at
       nearly every private university that has a graduate student union.

     o Costly union dues: Union members may pay dues of up to $550 per year,
       without any guarantee of better benefits or compensation.


   The UE and its supporters in the [21]MIT Graduate Student Union argue that
   a union would change campus for the better. It may also change it for the
   worse:

     o The UE would introduce a third-party entity on campus: The UE is a
       national organization with [22]its own political and financial
       interests, which may or may not align with yours. The UE can use
       member dues to advance these interests, including supporting its
       broader national organization, which is [23]something students opposed
       to the UE have raised concerns about. In addition to the UE's national
       political agenda, the new local union leadership would likely have its
       own priorities that you may or may not agree with.

     o The UE would be able to pressure students, and may continue to use
       students' personal information, even after a victory: We've received
       reports during this campaign of students feeling pressured by union
       supporters. Unfortunately, behavior like this is likely to persist if
       the UE is successful. The union would need to seek new student
       members, garner student support for their bargaining and political
       positions, and likely need to persuade students to strike. And it
       would still be able to access [24]personal contact information that
       MIT was required to produce last month. (Students may contact our
       [25]Institute Discrimination & Harassment Response Office or
       [26]Office of Student Conduct and Community Standards (OSCCS) if they
       have experienced any conduct that violates MIT policy).

     o The UE will impact student-advisor relationships: We know that [27]the
       overwhelming majority of graduate students have a positive view of the
       quality of academic advising and guidance as well as their
       interactions with faculty.

       Institute Professor Phillip Sharp and Professor Alan Grossman have
       authored [28]an op-ed in The Tech about the consequences a union would
       have on student-advisor relationships. Among their observations: "a
       unionized environment...reduces flexibility in favor of a highly
       structured relationship between manager and workers. We believe that
       such industry-framed relationships are ill-suited to the nature of and
       rapidly evolving opportunities in graduate education, where
       individuality and flexibility are necessary to foster a dynamic
       trajectory for graduate students".


   Every eligible student [29]should critically assess the different
   positions in this debate and vote on April 4 or 5 in Morss Hall, Walker
   Memorial (Building 50). This election's outcome will be determined by a
   simple majority of those who vote, but will be binding on everyone in the
   [30]proposed bargaining unit -- even if you don't vote, or don't want a
   union.

   Sincerely,

   Melissa Nobles
   Chancellor

   Ian A. Waitz
   Vice Chancellor for Undergraduate and Graduate Education

