    Breadcrumb

    1. [9]Home
    2. December 2022 updates

                             December 2022 updates

Negotiations

     o Nine bargaining sessions have been held this semester, most of which
       were full-day sessions. MIT and the MIT GSU-UE have been working their
       way through over 100 [10]non-economic provisions brought forth by the
       union.
     o These provisions are organized into 22 contract articles that MIT and
       the MIT GSU-UE have been exchanging. We have reached a tentative
       agreement on several articles and are close to an agreement on many
       others.**
     o The union***s proposals, which would apply to bargaining unit members
       across all of MIT***s 109 graduate programs, are thoughtful and
       comprehensive. We have spent the most time discussing concerns raised
       by the union on our health and safety processes, resources for
       international students, and our processes for responding to sexual
       misconduct and harassment. MIT administrators and faculty who have
       expertise on these topics have attended bargaining sessions to listen
       to and consider the union***s proposals. We also have been exploring
       peer practices on these issues and providing data and information to
       union negotiators so we are working from a common set of facts.
     o In the coming weeks, the union will present its economic proposals,
       which will include items such as stipends and benefits. Once we
       receive these proposals, we will work diligently with the union; with
       departments, labs, and programs; and with other stakeholders to reach
       an agreement.

Systems

     o Multiple MIT information systems and appointments processes will need
       to be updated to better track appointment information and to ensure
       compliance with the final contract between MIT and the MIT GSU-UE.**
     o All graduate students, as well as administrators who use these
       systems, can expect to see changes and/or enhancements in the coming
       weeks and months.**

Petition to add fellows

     o The [11]MIT GSU-UE filed a petition in September seeking to add
       students on fellowships to the existing bargaining unit. The NLRB held
       a hearing in late October on the issue.
     o During the hearing, the MIT GSU-UE argued that all fellows are
       employees because they conduct thesis research, which advances MIT***s
       mission of creating ***new knowledge,*** and they receive pay from
       MIT.
     o [12]MIT and [13]the union filed post-hearing briefs on November 10.
       Among other issues, MIT raised serious concerns about the union***s
       argument that all thesis research constitutes employment services, and
       the negative consequences that such equivalency would have, in
       particular, on international students. The NLRB will decide this
       issue, a process that may take several months. We encourage you to
       read [14]this summary to learn more.
       **

   Community members with questions about unions and unionization that are
   not addressed on this website may contact**[15]gradunionquestions@mit.edu.

