    Breadcrumb

    1. [7]Home

                           Why students are voting no

   Over the past six months, MIT graduate students have written to The Tech
   to express their concerns with forming a union aligned with the [8]United
   Electrical, Radio & Machine Workers of America (UE).**

   Before you vote on April 4-5, consider the issues these students raise
   below, and then ask yourself: Has the UE made its case to you? Has it
   provided sufficient, rigorous evidence to support its claims and promises?
   Does the UE share your values?

   --------------------------------------------------------------------------

   [9]Why UE and what it stands for cannot represent MIT graduate students

   ***Voting yes would bind us for years to come to UE, an organization that,
   in addition to being a fiscally irresponsible choice, holds many positions
   that are unrepresentative of MIT graduate students.***These positions
   range from ill-advised to downright abhorrent; even more concerning is the
   way in which their documents distort facts, history, and context in order
   to advance their propaganda.***

   --------------------------------------------------------------------------

   [10]Why I***m voting ***no*** to the graduate student union

   ***I am concerned that a union contract will greatly reduce the
   flexibility MIT currently affords students and their advisors as they
   collaborate to answer novel research questions. This rigidity would
   ultimately reduce the quality of research MIT graduate students are able
   to conduct. Isn***t this quality of research and the freedom to work hard
   to solve unanswered questions what drew us all to MIT in the first
   place?***

   --------------------------------------------------------------------------

   [11]The UE isn***t the union the GSU claims it is

   ***I would support the Graduate Student Union (GSU) if they were
   unionizing without the UE. However, they have elected to choose a nearly
   bankrupt, predatory, and oppressive national union that supports none of
   our interests.***The UE needs us, but we do not need the UE.***

   --------------------------------------------------------------------------

   [12]Why we do not need a graduate student union at MIT

   ***In order to garner broad support for their campaign, the GSU organizers
   have begun to discredit themselves by claiming every possible issue on
   campus as something a union would solve. Every improvement is hailed as a
   ***GSU win,*** announced without any further proof that this is indeed the
   case.***But we are making great strides with our current amicable working
   relationship between the GSC and MIT.***

   --------------------------------------------------------------------------

   [13]Some concerns about unionization from a graduate student

   ***I previously worked for the government and was forced to be in a union.
   The rigidity and duration of the collective bargaining agreement imposed
   severe constraints on my ability to negotiate with superiors and optimize
   my work experience.***The prospects of unionizing are unclear, and the
   trade-offs to this point have been poorly defined by the GSU. This is not
   a free lunch, and, indeed, it is uncertain whether any manna is
   forthcoming.***

   --------------------------------------------------------------------------

   Express YOUR view by voting next Monday and Tuesday, April 4 and 5 in a
   secret-ballot election. More information is available at
   [14]grad-union.mit.edu.

