     o [8]Background

                                    Homepage

   [9]MIT Campus

   On April 6, 2022, Chancellor Melissa Nobles and Vice Chancellor Ian Waitz
   [10]announced the results of the April 4-5 graduate student unionization
   election; congratulated current and past MIT GSU-UE members on their four
   years of dedicated work that culminated in the union***s election; and
   committed to bargain in good faith with the union over the terms and
   conditions of employment for bargaining unit members.

   Those initial negotiations will get underway in September 2022 and are
   likely to take at least several months to complete. At other universities
   with graduate student unions, negotiating a first contract has taken at
   least one year (from the date of certification to ratification) and, in
   several cases, multiple years.

   This website serves as a central resource with information about:

     o Which [11]graduate students are represented by the MIT GSU-UE.
     o The collective bargaining process and topics that are considered
       [12]mandatory subjects of bargaining and therefore must be discussed
       at the bargaining table.
     o Topics that are [13]non-mandatory subjects of bargaining, which means
       that employers can decide whether to bargain over them or to work
       through existing channels such as Institute committees or working
       groups.
     o The [14]latest updates, including letters and other announcements for
       the MIT community as well as, when finalized, the contract between MIT
       and the MIT GSU-UE.

   Community members with questions about unions and unionization that are
   not addressed on this website may contact**[15]gradunionquestions@mit.edu.

