     o [26]Bargaining Team

   [27]Home / Overview

   Since September 2022, the MIT bargaining team has been negotiating with
   MIT GSU on a first contract. More than 20 meetings, which are typically
   day-long sessions, have taken place and an additional bargaining session
   is scheduled for May 8. While MIT is committed to bargaining in good faith
   with the union over the terms and conditions of employment for bargaining
   unit members and reaching an agreement as quickly as possible, it is
   important to remember that negotiating first contracts at peer
   institutions have taken more than one year on average.

   MIT's principles guiding the negotiations include:

     o Fulfilling our responsibility to serve the entire community,
       understanding implications on overall enterprise, including all
       graduate students and undergraduate students
     o Ensuring students have flexibility to make their own choices ***
       avoiding unnecessary mandates, including union membership
     o Refraining from bargaining on academic matters
     o Protecting the effectiveness of the research and discovery enterprise
     o Protecting the unique nature of teacher-learner relationship
     o Ensuring the Institute remains competitive and continues to attract
       top talent
     o Ensuring equity with respect to our other employees
     o Ensuring fiscal responsibility for this generation at MIT and future
       generations

   As the Institute negotiates a wide range of economic and non-economic
   issues *** from grievance and harassment procedures to health benefits ***
   the bargaining team will need to evaluate any potential trade-offs on how
   MIT's departments, labs and centers, and the Institute overall, operate.
   MIT is encouraged that, to date, both sides have been collegial during
   bargaining and discussions have been constructive.

   General Inquiries: [28]gradunionquestions@mit.edu**

